Tom Regan, an American philosopher who specialized in animal rights theory, professor emeritus of philosophy at North Carolina State University, "The Case for Animal Rights" (1983):


[18th-century French philosopher and physician Julien Offay de La Mettrie challenges Descartes‚Äô view that humans should, but animals should not, be viewed as conscious beings because humans have immortal souls and animals do not. Thus, Descartes explains animal behavior in terms of ‚Äúmechanical‚Äù stimulation, like pinball machines]:


LaMettrie suggests that Descartes‚Äô views on the human mind (soul) was a concession he made to the powerful theologians of his day. Descartes‚Äô teaching regarding the human mind, La Mettrie writes, is ‚Äúplainly but a trick of skill, a ruse of style, to make theologians swallow a poison hidden in the shape of an analogy‚Ä¶. For it is this, this strong analogy (between human and animal behavior), which forces all scholars and wise judges to confess that these proud and vain beings (i.e., theologians in particular and humans in general), more distinguished by their pride than by the name of men however much they wish to exalt themselves, are at bottom only machines which, though upright, walk on all fours.‚Äù

author: @jonvelde5730
text: My problem with this movie was not Deckard's dullness (as a character) but rather his haplessness.  His JOB is supposed to be retiring replicants.  He's been doing it for years. He's supposed to be an old-hand and yet, pretty much each of his four "targets" tosses him around like a rag-doll.  Even the snake-dancer beats him down and could have easily ended him, although she inexplicably chooses to flee after knocking him for a loop. It's just not believable that killing androids could be this guy's nine-to-five. He wouldn't have survived two weeks on the job. So that definitely interferes with suspension of disbelief.

Los Angeles 2019
Film del 1982 blade runner

Dello scrittore Philip k.Dick
In Italia lo abbiamo visto nel 1983 e fu subito uno di quei film cult fra gli appassionati di un certo tipo cinema , in quegli anni in Italia , certo non per il grande pubblico o pubblico mainstream , ma col passare degli anni questo film ha avuto sempre di pi√π gradimento da quando nel 1982 e 1983 usci nelle sale cinematografiche e che fu apprezzato molto ma non da molte persone che andavano al cinema in quegli anni , i grandi successi di pubblico , furono altri film che li ebbero nel 1982 , 1983 , nelle sale cinematografiche come pubblico e spettatori non certo questo film blade runner di rindley scott, un tipo di film ambientato nel futuro , di fantascienza, diverso dagli altri film del genere , che anche per questo mi piacque molto, dalla scenografia alla musica originale del film.

author: @paulchristman2456
text: The trailer that I saw in theaters in '82 was not quite two minutes long and showed no action scenes. In fact, it disclosed very little of the storyline, although it contained a lot of dialogue and narration. It did show some of the impressive sets, though. To me, it looked like a futuristic "Dragnet" episode, which, basically, "Blade Runner" is. But seeing the trailer, I was unable to determine that the plot of the film revolved around artificial humans at all ; as I said, I thought it was simply a crime drama set in the future, and the trailer didn't pique my interest at all. Finally three years later I rented a vhs copy of it, and it knocked me out !  I was disgusted with myself for not having given myself the pleasure of seeing it on the big screen. Such a kickass sci fi film ! Both visually astonishing and intelligent. About ten years later, I heard about Jean Luc Goddard's 1965 "Alphaville" and bought a VHS copy of it sight unseen. Another truly remarkable sci fi film which definitely inspired Ridley Scott's second science fiction masterpiece, the first being "Alien", of course.

author: @joemacpherson1664
text:
Saturday afternoon, June 26, 1982: I was 27 years old. A new science fiction film premiered on June 25 and every scheduled showing across The City of Los Angeles on that day was sold out. A day later, I was fortunate to arrive early enough at the Fox Theatre in Westwood Village, in L.A. Two friends and I anticipated all that would appear before us, on the silver screen. No one in the audience had seen the film yet, and Warner Brothers Studios conducted a campaign to divulge very little about Blade Runner before it opened. Mystery, suspense and surprise can go a long way. I never saw the official trailer; apparently, most of the audience never viewed it. At the cinema, we didn't know the marvels that waited for us.
There was a startled reaction in the sold out crowd, when the words LOS ANGELES NOVEMBER 2019 appeared in the very first scene. Remember, it's June 26, 1982 and we're Angelenos, seeing Blade Runner on it's second day of the opening weekend. Los Angeles! Our city! The Future! You could tell, everyone was already doing math on the distance of Time to The Future. Thirty seven years from now!
For the rest of the showing it was absolute silence, shock or gasps of surprise. It was overwhelming to behold. We were dazzled. Flying cars! Tremendous architecture and extraordinary displays of electric and Neon lights! Those huge, incredible motion image billboards! Gliding above the skyline, casting shadows on everything below, the unexpected visual magic of advertising zeppelins. WOW. And Replicants, and animatronic, robotic birds. We saw technology beyond 1982. There was so much more to discover in L.A.'s metropolis, in this future time: Underground subway systems, redefined public transport, redesigned traffic signals on crowded streets. Those enticing outdoor dining centers, audio visual telephone communications, a different spending currency, the New Style, the New Vogue Look, the nightlife!
In an atmosphere of continuous, overcast skies and rain that fell like veils upon the city, something else captured our senses. As each scene unfolded before us, through it all, weaving a tapestry of sound and mood, the nocturnal, beautiful and melancholy soundtrack composed by Vangelis.
One particular, heartbreaking sequence brought many people to tears. It happened to me and I wasn't alone in that moment, in the dark of this crowded theatre.
When the film ended, most of us stayed until the final credit rolled by. Angelenos, enthralled, bewildered, enraptured by our city, in November, 2019. Conversations began in the lobby, as crowds made their exit: "This is L.A. in the future?" "Will it really be like this?" "I don't know if I'm ready for this!" "How much of this could happen?" "Will we live to see it come true?"
It was so strange to leave the cinema, stepping outside into sunshine daylight. No clouds, no rain, no darkened sky. All too soon we returned to the Present.
That was June 26, 1982. Today is November 8, 2019. I was there, 37 years ago. I've lived to see The Future. It's not quite what was foreseen but ever since that Saturday afternoon, long ago, Blade Runner is my favorite Science Fiction Film above all others. Long live The Future!

I think it's funny Deckard barely kills any replicants in this movie (Just two) and yet he's considered a well established Blade Runner.

I think it's hugely overrated but it all boils down do the standards you choose to judge something thus what your opinion is based on.

author: @Cacowninja
text:
Totally contrasting opinion warning: I thought this movie was SHIT.

1. Story was dull as shit.

a. Didn't kill enough replicants: I mean Dekard is called a Blade Runner so I expected him to do all this bad ass stuff and kill at least 10 replicants. You know, to establish what he does for a living and yet he only really kills 2 out of six for what I remember. One of them got killed by the girl replicant who helped him, the main one died on his own, and as for the other 2 I forgot. He's supposed to be the best at his job yet he only kills 2 out of 6 without any help I mean come now.

b. Didn't seem that futuristic: Okay, we have replicants (whatever the fuck those are, movie doesn't make it really clear, I mean are they robots, cyborgs, clones, grown lifeforms, what are they?), a machine that's supposed to identfiy replicants), hover cars, space colonization, robot animals, bigger buildings, some kind of computer you zoom in on things with, and that's pretty much it. Our current year of 2016 is WAY more high tech other than the "future" elements that movie did portray. We have smart phones, blade less fans, hd tvs, green energy such as solar power, electronic cigarettes, LED embelled clothing and more. Movie didn't do a good job of convincing that this is the future. Also what's with all the fucking oil refineries in the movie? Oil use is declining in real life and yet in the movie Los Angeles appears to have more oil refineries up the butt than ever before.

c. Was very bland: Seriously it feels like NOTHING happened in the movie. Mostly just talking and traveling from one point of Los Angeles to the other. Very little fighting as I mentioned in subpoint a. This is supposed to be the best science fiction movie of all time yet barely anything happens and what does happen is super dull?

2. Story was hard to follow: Okay as I stated above not much happened making the movie very simplistic yet I STILL couldn't follow it! I didn't know what the characters were doing and why plus I couldn't remember who anyone's name. Also I barely remember who anyone was! Okay you've got Deckard, the blade runner, his replicant lover, Deckards bosses, the replicants, a key guy who worked them, a toy maker, etc.

I'll finish the rest of this comment later.
